{"rawJson":null,"m_plot":null,"m_cast":"Bryan Cranston as Robert Mazur / Bob Musella[3] | John Leguizamo as Emir Abreu[4] | Benjamin Bratt as Roberto Alcaino[5] | Diane Kruger as Kathy Ertz[6] | Yul Vazquez as Javier Ospina | Rubén Ochandiano as Gonzalo Mora Jr. | Juliet Aubrey as Evelyn Mazur[4] | Amy Ryan as Bonni Tischler[4] | Olympia Dukakis as Aunt Vicky | Joe Gilgun as Dominic | Said Taghmaoui as Amjad Awan | Tom Vaughan-Lawlor as Steve Cook [6] | Elena Anaya as Gloria Alcaino[4] | Carsten Hayes as Rudy Armbrecht | Juan Cely as the Informant | Jason Issacs as Mark Jackowski | Andy Beckwith as Joe | Bryan Cranston and John Leguizamo previously worked together in The Lincoln Lawyer.","m_reception":null,"m_production":"The project was first announced by The Hollywood Reporter on October 8, 2014, with Brad Furman as director and Bryan Cranston as Robert Mazur. Miriam Segal would produce the film for her Good Films banner along with George Films, while Relativity International was announced to sell the film to foreign distributors at the American Film Market.[3] On February 13, 2015, Diane Kruger was set to star for the unspecified female lead role.[6] Benjamin Bratt was set to star in the film as Roberto Alcanio, the agent's contact who dealt directly with cartel board members, including Escobar.[5] On March 10, 2015, more cast was added to the film, including John Leguizamo, Amy Ryan, Olympia Dukakis, Elena Anaya, and Juliet Aubrey.[4] Broad Green Pictures acquired the US rights to the film on May 21, 2015.[7] | Filming was previously set to begin in March 2015 in Tampa, Florida, but then moved to London and Paris.[8] According to SSN Insider, filming began on February 23, 2015.[9] On March 11, 2015, the studio confirmed that filming was underway in London, releasing a first-look image from the film.[2] The production would move to Florida at the end of April.[2] Filming began in Tampa on April 22, 2015, on location at the Port Tampa Bay.[10][11] On April 28, 2015, they filmed in Parkland Estates near the former home of Santo Trafficante, an infamous Tampa mob boss.[citation needed]","m_sequel":null,"m_based_on":"The Infiltrator  by Robert Mazur","m_directed_by":"Brad Furman","m_produced_by":"Paul M. Brennan Brad Furman Miriam Segal Don Sikorski","m_screenplay_by":"Ellen Brown Furman","m_story_by":null,"m_starring":"Bryan Cranston | Diane Kruger | Benjamin Bratt | John Leguizamo | Amy Ryan | Said Taghmaoui","m_music_by":"Chris Hajian","m_cinematography":"Joshua Reis","m_edited_by":"Luis Carballar Jeff McEvoy David Rosenbloom","m_production_company":"Good Films","m_distributed_by":"Broad Green Pictures","m_release_dates":"July 13, 2016 (2016-07-13) |  |  |  | ","m_running_time":null,"m_country":"United States","m_language":"English","m_budget":"$47.5 million[1] | The Infiltrator is an upcoming American crime drama film directed by Brad Furman and written by Ellen Brown Furman, based on the autobiography of the same name by Robert Mazur, a U.S. Customs special agent. Mazur helps bust Pablo Escobar's money-laundering organization by using his alias, \"Bob Musella\". The film stars Bryan Cranston, Diane Kruger, Benjamin Bratt, John Leguizamo and Amy Ryan. Filming began on February 23, 2015 in London. The film is scheduled to be released July 13, 2016. |  | ","m_box_office":null,"m_marketing":null,"m_reference":"^ Guzzo, Paul (October 8, 2014). \"Tampa story 'The Infiltrator' to start Bryan Cranston\". Retrieved March 22, 2015.  | ^ a b c Lesnick, Silas (March 11, 2015). \"Check Out Bryan Cranston and Diane Kruger in the First Still from The Infiltrator\". comingsoon.net. Retrieved March 12, 2015.  | ^ a b Szalai, Georg (October 8, 2014). \"Bryan Cranston Attached to Star in Thriller 'The Infiltrator'\". hollywoodreporter.com. Retrieved February 15, 2015.  | ^ a b c d e Tartaglione, Nancy (March 10, 2015). \"Amy Ryan, John Leguizamo & More Join 'The Infiltrator' With Bryan Cranston\". deadline.com. Retrieved March 12, 2015.  | ^